metadata.name: RGB Elementary Cellular Automaton #607
metadata.description:
Stephen Wolfram's Elementary Cellular Automaton where 3 different rules are drawn in the Red, Green and Blue color components of the image.

Rules are selected randomly among a pre-selection of 53 rules from which nice behaviors emerge.

Tokens can have a cell size in the [1; 20] range.

metadata.name: Southern Gothic #219
metadata.description:
‚ÄúSouthern Gothic‚Äù is my debut release on the fxhash platform. The project is created entirely through code. All copyrights are released to the holder of each image output, even for commercial purposes.

‚ÄúSouthern Gothic‚Äù borrows its name from the literary genre made famous by writers like Flannery O‚ÄôConnor and Carson McCullers. Rather than illustrating a singular setting, the code generates an entire rural townscape, thereby, blurring the boundaries between representation and narrative. The individual scenes are framed frontally with an intentionally flat aesthetic character, referencing traditional folk art of the American South. The absence of human figures within these scenes adds to their overwhelming sense of darkness and forlorn. Observing multiple scenes side-by-side, one may even get the strange feeling that something terrible has happened (or is about to happen) in this rural landscape.

Pressing the down arrow saves the coded output as a .png image.

metadata.name: the Glory of Colours #196
metadata.description:
According to Kandinsky, painting ‚Äúcan create the same energies in the observer that music can make in the listener. The abstract painter is an echo seeker: just like the relationship between music and the listener, shapes and colors must penetrate the observer's soul. They vibrate the threads of his existence and resonate in the depths of his mind, you can still find references to people, buildings, mountains, etc., but these are more signs than manifestations. They do not evoke objects but abstractly reveal them, like the simplified image we have seen before of objects and elements in nature.
Classical philosophy reinforces the belief that existing, tangible reality is a mask for a deeper reality that can only be reached through imagination. I have tried to combine this with the art of coding and creating canvases of millions of characters and numbers.
Made in p5js
Created July 2022
Artist: @ChistaAi

metadata.name: a formless beauty #26
metadata.description:
"a formless beauty" continues my exploration of pure abstract generative art. 

In this piece, I begin with a white field. An abstract pattern of rectangles are drawn on this field, using one of 12 different color palettes. On top of this, a white diamond or filled circle is drawn, and then marks (the term that IRL abstract painters will be familiar with) are drawn over the top of this. These three layers comprise the basis of the piece. 

Things are fairly deterministic so far, but this juncture, a large amount of randomness is introduced to the piece, as the image is passed through a fragment shader that applies fractal noise to the process, resulting in an image that appears to have been painted and then washed out. I would like to thank Melissa Wiederrecht for the inspiration in this regard; her Zbageti piece pushed me to explore shaders and their effect on the overall look of the piece. 

Note 1: Due to the nature of WebGL, this piece may not (probably will not) run in live mode on a mobile device. I've tested it on mobile Safari and mobile Chrome, and it will run sometimes, but the device is very unhappy with it. 

Note 2: Due to the nature of fractal noise and the preview engine in FxHash, the preview image will  be slightly different than the live view. It will give you a general idea of the piece, but the live view will be more vibrant and detailed.

Note 3: In Live view, press "s" to save a 4000x4000 PNG of the image to your system.

metadata.name: Ersbla #491
metadata.description:
Ersbla is part of the fxhash live minting experience at Proof of People, London 2022. 

It is the third entry in a series of abstract generative experiments inspired by the graphic and textile work of Anni and Josef Albers. As a follow-up to the 'Sabler' and 'Lebras' collections, 'Ersbla' produces textile effects using a combination of thousands of tiny dots arranged on variable grids, resulting in a wide variety of unique Bauhaus-inspired compositions in a variety of palettes.

Press 'S' to save a high-resolution 2400 x 3396 px image in PNG format.

Depending on the density of your output, please allow up to a few seconds for your edition to generate.
